description:
Putobumbong is the classic Filipino treat during the holiday season. It's made of sticky black rice rolled in freshly grated coconut and served with muscovado sugar. In this episode, I'll show you 2 ways to make putobumbong at home so you could make it for the holiday season and any time of year. For the full recipe, just go to: http://www.astigvegan.com

VERSION 1:
1 cup sweet black rice, pulverized using a high-speed blender (see note below)
½ cup water for soaking
¼ cup water for binding)
pinch of salt
oil to grease steamer

VERSION 2:
½ cup black rice, pulverized using a high-speed blender or if you don't have a blender, use purple yam powder (see note below)
½ cup glutinous white rice flour (see note below)
¾ cup water
pinch of salt
oil to grease steamer

CONDIMENTS:
grated coconut (see note below)
muscovado sugar (or organic dark brown sugar)
vegan butter or coconut oil (optional)

EQUIPMENT:
Steamer
High-speed blender (or use purple yam powder to skip having to pulverize rice)


To prevent getting rice all over your hands when forming the logs, you may dip your fingers in a small bowl of oil. 

You could buy sweet black rice at most asian and filipino grocery stores, or online. A reputable company, Eighth Wonder, sells high-quality Ifugao Diket sweet black rice exported from the Philippines.

You could buy regular black rice (also goes by forbidden black rice) at most specialty stores and asian grocery stores. I got mine at the bulk section of Rainbow Grocery San Francisco under the bulk section.

You could buy glutinous rice flour at most asian grocery stores and specialty stores (I got mine at Rainbow Grocery San Francisco under the bulk section). Make sure it says "glutinous" or "sticky". Regular rice flour will not produce a chewy texture.

You could buy grated coconut at most asian grocery stores, under the frozen section. Make sure it says "grated" and that it's from mature coconuts and not young ones. In tagalog, we call mature coconuts, "niyog". Fresh grated coconut is preferable over dried ones. You could also make grated coconut fresh from the husk.

You could buy muscovado sugar at most specialty stores and asian grocery stores and online. Muscovado sugar is made of unrefined sugarcane juice. It has more molasses content and has a caramel flavor. If you couldn't find muscovado sugar, you may use organic dark brown sugar (most non-organic dark brown sugar are not vegan because they use bone char during the refining process).
